Nc3 d6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. h3 {An interesting way to fight the Najdorf.} g6 ({
The two have lready discussed the consequences of:} 4... a6 5. a4 Nc6 6. d4
cxd4 7. Nxd4 g6 {In another blitz game:} 8. Be3 Bg7 9. g3 O-O 10. Bg2 Bd7 11.
O-O Ne5 12. Nde2 {Nakamura,H (2769)-Vachier Lagrave,M (2789) Paris 2018}) 5. d4
cxd4 6. Nxd4 Bg7 7. g3 Nc6 8. Be3 O-O 9. Bg2 {[%csl Gg2]} Nxd4 10. Bxd4 Be6 ({
Another plan for Black is connected with:} 10... Bd7 11. Qe2 Rc8 {[%cal Gc8c2]}
12. O-O Bc6 13. e5 dxe5 14. Bxe5 Qb6 15. a4 Bxg2 16. Kxg2 {1/2-1/2 (16)
Andreikin,D (2723)-Bok,B (2598) Minsk 2017}) 11. O-O a6 12. Re1 Rc8 13. Nd5
Bxd5 (13... Nd7 $5 {[%cal Gd7c5,Gd7e5]}) 14. exd5 {[%csl Gd5,Re7,Rf7,Rg6,Rh7]
[%cal Gd5e6] [#]} Nd7 $146 {A novelty. However, at this stage of the game it
seems as Black is already doing not that well.} ({White was also better after:
} 14... Re8 15. Re2 Nd7 16. Bxg7 Kxg7 17. Qd4+ Nf6 18. g4 $1 {[%csl Rf6,Rg7]
[%cal Gf2f4,Gg4g5,Ga1e1] in the predecessor Mista,A (2609) -Areshchenko,A 
(2701) Warsaw 2014}) 15. Bxg7 Kxg7 16. c3 {[%csl Re7,Rg7] The backward pawn on
e7 is a big issue and White is pretty much better all over the place. In the
center he has the more active pieces, he has pawn majority on the queenside,
but the real problem is the weak black king.} Re8 17. Qd4+ Kg8 18. Re2 {
[%csl Ge7][%cal Ge1e7]} Qb6 {If Black can only trade the ueens off this will
make his life so much easier as he would be able to defend the e7 weakness
with the king.} 19. Qh4 $1 {But this is not going to happen.} Ne5 {The knight
is not stable here and will be soon chased away thus providing time for the
White's kingside assault.} ({Perhaps MVL should have adopted a slightly
different defensive set-up with:} 19... Kg7 $5 20. Rae1 Nf6 21. a3 Rc7 {
[%csl Re7][%cal Rc7e7,Re8e7]}) 20. Kh2 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gf2f4,Gg3g4,Gf4f5,
Ga1e1] Nakamura slowly prepares for the opening of the kingside.} Kg7 21. Rd1
Rc4 22. Qg5 ({Also good, but somewhat unnatural is:} 22. f4 Qb5 23. Red2) 22...
h6 23. Qd2 Rc7 24. Rde1 Qb5 ({If Black tries something active like:} 24... Nc4
25. Qc2 Qc5 {[%csl Rc4] Then not much will be changed as the knight still
lacks ouposts and is vulnerable. For example:} 26. b3 Ne5 27. f4 Nd7 28. Rxe7
Rxe7 29. Rxe7 Kf8 30. Qe2 Qxc3 31. Re8+ Kg7 32. Rd8 $1 {[%cal Re2e8,Re8h8]
with mighty attack.} ({But not the hasty} 32. Qe7 Qf6 $1 {and Black is out of
the bush.})) 25. f4 {All is ready for the decisive kingside action.} Nc4 ({
Similar is:} 25... Nd3 26. Rd1 Nc5 27. f5) 26. Qd4+ Kg8 27. b3 Nb6 ({Or} 27...
Na5 28. c4 Qb4 29. f5 $1 {wehn Black lacks kingside defenders.}) 28. c4 Qa5 ({
After:} 28... Qc5 {White can swap the queens off for a change:} 29. Qxc5 dxc5
30. d6 {[%csl Rc7,Re7][%cal Rd6c7,Rd6e7] and for an extra pawn.}) 29. f5 $1 {
[%csl Ra5,Rb6,Rc7,Rg8] With the black pieces desperately stuck on the opposite
wing the attack is a piece of cake for Nakamura.} g5 {Played instantly, but
the position cannot be blocked.} ({If} 29... gxf5 30. Rf1 e6 31. Rxf5 $1 {
[%cal Rd4g4,Rf5h5] wins for White.}) 30. f6 $1 Nd7 $1 {Vachier-Lagrave tries
his final chance to block the white pieces.} (30... Nc8 {loses effortlessly
after} 31. h4 $1 {[%csl Rg8][%cal Rh4g5,Rd4g4]}) ({Whereas:} 30... Kf8 31.
fxe7+ Rcxe7 32. Qh8# {is a typical line.}) 31. fxe7 ({Not} 31. Rxe7 $6 Qxe1 $1
32. Rxe1 Rxe1 33. Qd2 Re8 {which complicates matters at least.}) 31... Ne5 {
It seems as Black is holding, but...} ({If:} 31... Qc5 32. Qd2 Ne5 {Then the
way to unblock the pawn avalanche is:} 33. b4 Qxc4 34. Rxe5 $1 dxe5 35. d6 {
promoting.}) 32. c5 $3 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Rc7c5,Rd6c5,Ra5c5] On three-times
defended square.} ({Instead:} 32. Rxe5 $2 dxe5 33. Rxe5 Rcxe7 {would be
anything but clear.}) 32... Ng6 {Everything loses.} (32... Qxc5 33. Qxc5 Rxc5
34. Rxe5 dxe5 35. d6 {[%cal Gd6d7] would see the white pawns promoted.}) ({
Whereas} 32... Rxc5 33. b4 Qa4 34. Rxe5 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Rb4c5,Rd4c5] wins
material for White.}) 33. cxd6 Rd7 34. Qf6 Qb6 35. Rf1 Nh8 36. Re6 $1 {[%csl
Ge6] A nice finishing touch.} fxe6 37. Qf8+ Rxf8 38. exf8=Q+ Kh7 39. Be4+ Ng6 (
{Not waiting for the mate, Vachier-Lagrave throws in the towel:} 39... Ng6 40.
Bxg6+ Kxg6 41. Rf6+ Kh7 42. Rxh6#) 1-0

