92,86,78,74,85,99,90,70,42,42,33,87,78,63,84,90,75,89,91,89,94,93,92,89,98,98,
98,109,104,113,104,109,126,139,138,137,144,152,113,123,126,124,129,117,117,127,
132,162,132,130,85,141,150,138,170,164,166,169,162,150,168,162,169,166,142,167,
166,827,1255]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 g6 {One can never guess what opening the world
champion will choose.} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. c4 Nf6 6. Nc3 d6 7. Be2 Nxd4
8. Qxd4 Bg7 9. O-O O-O 10. Qd3 {Still, the choice of the solid but passive
Accelerated Dragon seems comfortable for Giri.} a5 11. Be3 Bd7 ({One of the
major experts of the line as Black could not solve comletely his opening
problems after:} 11... a4 {[%cal Gd8a5]} 12. Bd4 Qa5 13. Rad1 Re8 14. f4 e5 15.
fxe5 dxe5 16. Be3 Be6 17. Nd5 {[%csl Gc4,Gd5,Ge4] with pleasant central
pressure for White in Wei,Y (2725) -Zvjaginsev,V (2627) China 2019}) 12. Bd4 $5
{[%mdl 4] White is ready to swap the dark-squared bishops, although he often
prefers not to do so in the Accelerated Dragon.} Bc6 13. b3 $5 {[%mdl 4]
Following the restrictive, small advantage line.} Nd7 14. Bxg7 ({White
sometimes simply leaves the opponent's fianchettoed bishop on the diagonal,
and then clears it out of his pieces. But here:} 14. Be3 {is connected with a
pawn sacrifice:} Nc5 15. Qc2 Bxc3) 14... Kxg7 15. Qd4+ {[#]} Kg8 $146 ({
The predecessor witnessed a quick draw after:} 15... f6 16. Nd5 (16. f4 Qb6)
16... e5 17. Qe3 Bxd5 18. cxd5 {[%csl Ga5,Gd6,Gd7,Ge5,Gf6][%cal Gd7c5,Gf6g5,
Gd6c5,Ga5b4] 1/2-1/2 (18) Gorbunov,E (2065)-Waerstad,L (2146) ICCF email 2018})
16. Rfd1 {An interesting choice.} ({The other rook seems more suitable for
this square:} 16. Rad1 $5 Qb6 17. Qxb6 Nxb6 18. f4 {[%cal Gf1f8] as the f1 is
already workign on the kingside and the center.}) 16... Qb6 {Black is happy to
swap the queens off as without the fianchettoed bishop he always risks to get
under tremendous kingside attack with f2-f4-f5.} 17. Qxb6 Nxb6 18. f4 f5 {
However, this is a bit risky. Carlsen tries to solve his problems dynamically,
concretely.} ({Safer looks:} 18... Nd7 $5 {[%cal Gd7c5,Ge7e5] Intending Nd7-c5
and later in a proper moment e7-e5. In this case Black might have feared:} 19.
Nd5 {When:} Bxd5 ({However, the patient:} 19... Rae8 $1 {would have kept
things in order for the second player.}) 20. Rxd5 $1 Nf6 21. Rb5 {[%csl Ra5,
Rb7][%cal Rb5b7,Rb5a5] is indeed a pleasant egde for White.}) ({Also good
seemed the careful play for dark-squared blockade with:} 18... f6 $5 {followed
by Kg8-f7 and the same knight maneuver.}) 19. exf5 $1 {[%cal Ge1e7,Gf1f7] The
correct reaction. Giri opens the central files for his rooks.} Rxf5 ({After:} 
19... gxf5 {White has pleasant pressure along the files with the immediate:}
20. Re1 {[%csl Rd6,Re7][%cal Re1e7,Ra1d1,Rd1d6,Gg1f2,Ge2f3]} ({Or the slightly
more refined:} 20. Rd3 {[%csl Rd6,Re7][%cal Gd3e3,Ga1e1,Ge2f3,Gf3h5,Re3e7]}))
20. g3 g5 {The same dynamical policy.} 21. Bd3 ({More accurate was:} 21. Bg4 $1
{[%cal Gg4e6]} Rc5 22. Re1 Re8 (22... gxf4 23. Rxe7) 23. Ne4 Bxe4 24. Rxe4 {
[%csl Rb6,Gg4] with an edge for White.}) 21... Rc5 22. Re1 Re8 ({Here Carlsen
missed:} 22... gxf4 $1 23. Rxe7 fxg3 24. hxg3 Rh5 $1 {[%cal Rc8h3] This is
possible since the white bishop does not control the diagonal. Black is very
close to equality, e.g.:} 25. Be4 d5 26. cxd5 Nxd5 27. Nxd5 Bxd5 28. Bxd5+ Rxd5
29. Rxb7 Rd2 {in both cases the active black rooks and the reduced material
should be enough to maintain the balance.} ({Or:} 29... a4)) 23. Ne4 $1 {
Forces a favorable endgame.} Bxe4 24. Rxe4 gxf4 25. Rxf4 {[%csl Rb6,Gd3,Rd6,
Re7]} Nd7 26. Re1 Ne5 27. Be4 {The endgame is very unpleasant for Black- the
bishop is superior to the knight, and the White's pawn structure favors him in
almost all the endgames.} b5 {More pawn trades are desirable for the defender.}
28. cxb5 Rxb5 29. Rh4 (29. Rf5 $1 {would have also kept White in control.})
29... Rb4 {Carlsen decided to part with the pawn.} ({Strong seemed to be:} 
29... Ng6 $1 {with the idea:} 30. Rg4 ({However, White has instead:} 30. Bc6 $1
{Which forces won pawn endgame after:} Nxh4 31. Bxe8 Nf3+ 32. Kf2 Rf5 33. Bd7
$1 Rf7 34. Be6 Nxe1+ 35. Kxe1 Kf8 36. Bxf7 Kxf7 37. a3 {[%cal Gb3b4,Gh2h3,
Gg3g4,Gh3h4,Gg4g5,Gb4b5] This is what I meant when saying that White's pawns
are of higher quality in the endgame. The distant passers are getting promoted
by themselves.}) 30... Re5 $1 31. Bxg6 Rxe1+ 32. Kf2 hxg6 $11 {and a draw.})
30. Bxh7+ Kg7 31. Be4 {White is up a pawn, plus he kept all the other
advantages of his position and therefore should be winning. But still, try
winning this against the world champion...} a4 (31... Rh8 $5 {at once also
made sense.}) 32. bxa4 Rxa4 33. Re2 Rh8 34. Rxh8 Kxh8 35. Bd5 Ra5 ({Perhaps
the active approach:} 35... Rd4 36. Bb3 Kg7 {would have been more stubborn.})
36. Bb3 {Next Giri carefully consolidates.} Nc6 37. Rd2 Kg7 38. Kg2 Ne5 39. h3
Nd7 40. Re2 Kf8 41. Rf2+ Nf6 42. g4 Kg7 43. Rf4 d5 44. g5 {But here he rushed
a bit.} (44. h4 $1 {keeping the pawns together would have been more technical.}
) 44... Ne4 45. Bxd5 Nxg5 46. Bb3 e5 {As strange as it sounds, but this only
helps White as the seventh rank is weakened.} ({Instead the powerful
centralization:} 46... Re5 $1 47. h4 Ne4 {was still promising Carlsen
defensive chances.}) 47. Ra4 $1 {Very nice!} Rc5 ({Without the rooks, the
a-passer is a Speedy Gonzales:} 47... Rxa4 48. Bxa4 Ne4 49. Bc6 Nc3 50. a3 $1 (
50. a4 $2 Nxa4 $1)) 48. Rc4 {Missing the instant win in the time-scramble.} ({
It was a good moment for a couple of in-between moves:} 48. h4 $1 Nh7 49. Rg4+
Kf6 {and then:} 50. Rc4 {winning.}) 48... Ra5 49. h4 Ne6 50. Ra4 Nf4+ $1 {
Now the knight reached its optimal position.} 51. Kf3 Rc5 52. Rc4 Ra5 53. Rc7+
Kh6 54. Bc2 Ra3+ 55. Kg4 {However, Giri is still clearly on top, neatly
surrounding the enemy king.} Nd3 56. Kf5 Nb4 {Without the knight around, the
black king goes down in flames.} ({The last chance was:} 56... e4 $5 57. Kxe4
Nb4 58. Ke5 Nxc2 59. Rxc2 {[%cal Gc2h2,Gh4h5,Ge5d5,Gd5c5,Gc5b4] although this
is also a textbook win according to the tablebases.}) 57. Be4 $1 Rxa2 58. Kg4
1-0

