-21,-41,-36,3,3,0,0,20,20,87,91,88,76,165,178,170,184,181,203,218,179,222,187,
187,154,193,180,191,188,239,304,413,136,129,118,108,108,108,128,124,124,116,
118,116,126,126,127,127,137,182,137,144,136,163,-29979,-29980,-29981,-29982,
-29983,-29980,-29981,-29982]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3
a6 6. Bd3 e6 7. f4 Qc7 8. Qe2 b5 9. a3 Nbd7 10. O-O Bb7 11. Nf3 Be7 12. Bd2 O-O
13. Rae1 Rac8 14. Kh1 ({White's set-up is designed for a central attack.
However:} 14. e5 Nd5 15. Nxd5 Bxd5 {[%csl Gd6][%cal Ge7d6] does not lead him
anywhere.}) ({Also an attempt to bring some pieces for a kingside attack with:
} 14. Nd1 {[%cal Rd1f2,Rf2g4,Gd1e3,Ge3g4] is harmless for Black after:} Nc5 {
[%csl Re4]}) 14... Nc5 15. b4 ({Once again Black will simply ignore his
opponent in case of:} 15. e5 Nfd7 {[%csl Re5,Rf4][%cal Rf1f4,Re1e5]}) 15...
Nxd3 16. cxd3 Qd7 {[%cal Gc8c1] Preparing counterplay along the c-file.
Korobov's position is quite pleasant.} 17. Nd4 Rc7 18. Na2 $5 {[%cal Ga2c1,
Gc1b3,Gb3a5] Karjakin maneuvers his knight towards the a5 outpost.} ({More
natural seemed to send the knight to e3 in order to fight for the d5 square
after a possible f4-f5, while at the same time defending the entry square on
c2.} 18. Nd1 {[%cal Gd1e3,Rd4b3,Rb3a5]}) 18... Rfc8 19. Nc1 g6 20. Ncb3 e5 {
Korobov feels that the knights are not optimally placed, and this is a good
time to break open the position for the bishops.} ({However, more solid (and
sound) was to slowly build the position with:} 20... Bf8 {[%cal Gf8g7]} 21. Na5
Ba8 {[%cal Ga8h1,Gf8g7,Gg7a1]}) 21. fxe5 dxe5 22. Nf3 Qe6 23. Nc5 $1 {[%csl
Rf6][%cal Rf1f6] An additional chance was presented thanks to the opening of
the f-file. Black has to be careful now!} Bxc5 24. bxc5 Rxc5 $2 {And he is not!
} ({Corerct was to keep the rook on the seventh rank to defend the f7 pawn
with:} 24... Nh5 $1 {Then:} 25. Ng5 {can be met with either:} Qa2 ({Or} 25...
Qb3 {in both cases with roughly equal game.})) 25. Ng5 Qe7 {Accepting the loss
of the exchange.} ({The only square on which the queen and the c5 rook were
not pinned was:} 25... Qc6 {However, this loses to:} 26. Nxf7 $1 Kxf7 27. Bg5 {
[%csl Rf6][%cal Rf1f6,Rg5f6] when White regains the material with a strong
attack.}) 26. Bb4 h6 27. Nf3 a5 28. Bxc5 Rxc5 29. Qd2 {Another double attack.
Karjakin is winning.} Kg7 30. Qxa5 Nh5 31. Qb4 Qc7 32. Qd2 ({More solid was:} 
32. Qb2 Qd6 33. Rd1 {[%cal Gd3d4]}) 32... Qd6 33. g3 $6 {Why open the diagonal
against his king without any necessity? In blitz!?} ({It was not too late to
revert to the line from above with:} 33. Qb4 $1) 33... f5 $1 {Now it gets very,
very messy.} 34. exf5 gxf5 35. Kg1 Nf6 (35... Kh7 {was more accurate, not
allowing knight forks.}) 36. Nh4 Qc6 {This is why the long diagonal should not
have been opened. Karjakin has to think about defense as well, not only about
converting the material advantage.} 37. Qg2 ({With seconds on the clock it is
easy to miss brilliancy:} 37. Nxf5+ $1 Kf7 38. Re4 $3 {[%csl Re4,Rf7][%cal
Rf1f7]} Qb6 (38... Nxe4 39. dxe4 {is also hopeless for Black.}) 39. Qxh6 $1 {
[%csl Gg1] and none of the discovered checks can save Black.}) 37... Qb6 $1 {
There are so many problems on the diagonals now!} 38. Nxf5+ Kh7 39. Qh3 $1 {
[%csl Rg1][%cal Rh3h6,Rh6g7] But Karjakin does not tremble and creates mating
threats on his own!} Rc2+ 40. d4 $1 ({If White sacrifices the queen with:} 40.
Ne3 Rg2+ 41. Qxg2 Bxg2 42. Kxg2 Qc6+ {It is not clear, the queen is very good
whenever the enemy king lacks safety.}) 40... Ng4 $1 {[%cal Gc2g2] Exclam for
the courage!} ({It was not too late to switch to a similar line to the one
from above with:} 40... Rg2+ 41. Qxg2 Bxg2 42. Kxg2 Qc6+ 43. Kh3 e4) 41. Ne3 $1
({There was a curious draw:} 41. Re4 $5 {This drags the bishop closer to the
white queen. Then after:} Bxe4 42. Qxg4 Rg2+ 43. Kh1 Re2+ {The only square to
defend the bishop.} 44. Kg1 {leads to perpetual.}) 41... Qxd4 42. Rf7+ $1 {
The only move.} ({Black is mating after:} 42. Qxg4 Rg2+ $1 ({But note that
moves cannot be transposed:} 42... Qxg4 {with the idea:} 43. Nxg4 ({Is refuted
by the same in-between check:} 43. Rf7+ $1 {[%cal Gg1f1] when the white king
gets breathing room.}) 43... Rg2+ 44. Kh1 Rxg3+ {and mate.}) 43. Kh1 Rxg3+)
42... Kg6 43. Rxb7 Nxe3 {Black is almost mating, but it is White who starts
the checks first.} 44. Qe6+ Kh5 45. Qf7+ {Karjakin wants to mate.} ({Otherwise,
he could have repeated with:} 45. Qh3+ Kg6 ({As Black cannot deviate:} 45...
Kg5 $4 46. Rg7+ Kf6 47. Qxh6+ Kf5 48. Qg6#) 46. Qe6+) 45... Kg5 ({Better was:} 
45... Kg4 $1 46. Qd7+ Kf3 47. Qxd4 exd4 48. Rd7 Ke4 {and because of his active
pieces Black should hold this.}) 46. Qg7+ ({I am not sure that White would
have found the win here even in a classical game.} 46. Qe7+ $1 Kf5 47. Qd7+ Ke4
{Now comes the compcool:} 48. Qh3 $3 {Which defends everything and puts Black
in some sort of a zugwang. White is winning, say:} Kd3 49. Rd7 Nd5+ 50. Kh1 {
The pins are awesome for the first player.}) 46... Kh5 47. Qf7+ Kg5 48. Rd7 {
A blunder, which could have lost the game.} Rg2+ 49. Kh1 {Here comes the
swindle:} Rxh2+ $1 50. Kg1 Rg2+ 51. Kh1 Rh2+ {The peace was signed here.} ({
A pity, there was a second swindle, hidden a bit:} 51... Rh2+ 52. Kg1 Rh1+ $3 {
With mate after:} 53. Kxh1 Qe4+ {[%csl Rg2][%cal Re4g2]}) 1/2-1/2

