c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. a3 {This appears to the the
most popular line in Wijk so far.} e5 7. Nf5 {" I checked it (this move)
yesterday." Carlsen.} ({Karjakin chose a different way yesterday:} 7. Nf3 Be7 (
7... b5 8. Bg5 Be7 9. Bxf6 Bxf6 10. a4 b4 11. Nd5 {Harikrishna,P (2763) -Giri,
A (2790) Stavanger 2016}) 8. Bc4 Be6 9. Ba2 O-O 10. O-O b5 11. Re1 Re8 12. Bg5
{Karjakin,S (2785)-Giri,A (2773) Tata Steel Masters 2017}) 7... d5 {The most
principled line. The dangers of the capture on f5 are demonstrated by this
short game:} (7... Bxf5 8. exf5 d5 9. Bg5 {[%csl Rd5,Re4]} d4 10. Bxf6 Qxf6 11.
Nd5 {[%cal Rd5c7,Rd5f6]} Qc6 12. c4 {[%cal Gf1d3,Gd3e4,Gf1e2,Ge2f3]} dxc3 13.
Rc1 Bc5 $2 14. Rxc3 a5 15. Bb5 {[%csl Rc6,Re8][%cal Rd5c7] 1-0 (15) Schou
Moldt,T (2210) -Skrabakova,K (2000) Teplice 2012}) 8. Bg5 d4 (8... dxe4 {
is bad due to} 9. Qxd8+ Kxd8 10. Rd1+ Kc7 11. Nxg7 {[%cal Rg5f6]} ({Or} 11.
Bxf6 gxf6 12. Nd5+) 11... Bxg7 12. Bxf6 {[%csl Rd5,Re4][%cal Rc3d5] in both
cases with advantage for White.}) 9. Bxf6 Qxf6 $146 {A novelty by Wojtaszek.
Three previous games saw instead :} (9... gxf6 {For example:} 10. Ne2 Nc6 11.
Neg3 Ne7 12. Nxe7 (12. Bd3 $5) 12... Bxe7 13. Be2 Qa5+ 14. b4 Qc7 15. O-O {
Ramesh,R (2491)-Arun Prasad,S (2384) Hyderabad 2006}) 10. Nd5 Qd8 {Perhaps
Black will try next time:} (10... Qc6 $5 {when} 11. Qg4 g6 12. Qg3 Nd7 13. Nxd4
{does not seem dangerous because of} exd4 14. Nc7+ Kd8 15. Nxa8 b5 {[%csl Ra8]}
) 11. Qg4 $1 {[%cal Gf5g7] "I think he missed this stuff." Carlsen.} Bxf5 {
The main point of the line is that:} (11... g6 {is bad due to} 12. Qg3 {When}
gxf5 $2 ({While} 12... Nc6 {Allows the cute} 13. Nxd4 $1 {[%cal Rd5c7]} exd4 (
13... Nxd4 14. Qxe5+ {[%csl Re8][%cal Re5d4,Re5h8,Re5e8]}) 14. Nc7+ {and White
wins material. This line should be investigated further since the white knight
might get trapped on a8, but I am pretty sure that the world champion had done
his homework.}) 13. Qxe5+ {drops the rook on h8.}) 12. Qxf5 {[%csl Gf1,Rf8]}
Bd6 13. h4 $1 {[%cal Gh1h3,Gh3g3,Gg3f3] An important move. Carlsen intends to
shift his rook on the third rank for a kingside attack. The "h" pawn will also
do a good job going forward.} Nc6 14. Bc4 b5 15. Bb3 Ne7 {Wojtaszek cannot
tolerate the white knight for sure.} 16. Qg4 O-O 17. Rh3 Nxd5 18. Bxd5 {
[%csl Gd5,Rd6] A typical Najdorf position arose, one of the tough ones for
Black. This one may be called the second worse for Black. In our GTD from
yesterday, we saw the worst one- good knight versus bad bishop. The
opposite-colored bishops with heavy pieces on the board are quite scary too.
The main problem is the f7 square. Black always has to defend it passively.
But that is not all. White can also attack on the "h" file, the "a" file and
even on the "c" one later. To cut a long story short- the one who has the
better bishop has the long-term pressure.} Ra7 19. Rg3 Qf6 ({Or} 19... g6 20.
h5 {[%csl Rg6][%cal Rh5g6,Rg4g6] with the threat to take twice on g6.}) 20. a4
{The "a" file. The white rook on a1 is the only piece that can do better at
the moment.} ({Carlsen avoids} 20. O-O-O Qf4+ {[%csl Rf4,Rg4]}) 20... Bb4+ 21.
Kf1 bxa4 22. Rxa4 a5 {Depriving the rook of access to the "c" file:} (22... Bd6
23. Rc4 {[%csl Rg7][%cal Gc4c6,Gc6d6,Rg4g7]}) 23. Ra1 Rc7 24. Bb3 Ra8 25. Kg1
Bf8 26. Qh5 {[%csl Rf7][%cal Rg3f3,Rf3f7] White provokes another weakening.
The threat is Rg3-f3.} g6 ({Black can hardly avoid this. If} 26... Raa7 27. Rf3
Qd6 28. Ra4 {[%cal Ga4c4] the rook will make it to c4 anyway.}) 27. Qg4 $6 {
This seems imprecise. Better was the preliminary} (27. Rf3 Qd6 ({Perhaps
Carlsen disliked the endgame after} 27... gxh5 28. Rxf6) 28. Qg5 {with a clear
advantage.}) 27... Ra6 $6 {"Quite a poor move." Carlsen.} ({Wojtaszek should
have taken the queens from the board instead with} 27... Qf4 $1 28. Qxf4 exf4
29. Rd3 Bg7 {with good chances to survive in the endgame.}) ({The computer
suggests instead} 27... a4 28. Rxa4 Rxa4 29. Bxa4 Bh6 {with the idea} 30. Bb3
Qf4 31. Qxf4 Bxf4 32. Rf3 Bc1 $11) 28. h5 Qf4 {The king cannot hide easily:} (
28... Kh8 29. Rh3 {[%csl Rh8][%cal Rh5g6,Rh3h8]}) ({Or} 28... Bg7 29. hxg6 hxg6
30. Rf3 Qd8 31. Ra4 {with clear edge.}) 29. Qe2 $1 {That is the difference in
comparison to the immediate Qf6-f4. The queens remain on the board, and with
the, White's attack is significantly stronger.} (29. Qxf4 exf4 30. Rg5 Rc5 {
would have kept Black into the game.}) 29... Qf6 30. Qb5 {Black's position is
ready to collapse.} ({Also good was:} 30. Rf3 Qc6 31. Bd5 Qb6 32. Ra4) 30...
Qc6 {Drops a pawn. Black's best chance was:} (30... Rc5 31. hxg6 $5 ({Or} 31.
Qd7 Qe7 32. hxg6 hxg6 33. Qg4) ({Carlsen could also repeat the moves with} 31.
Qe2 {and come back to the Ra1-a4-c4 idea.}) {with the idea} 31... Rxb5 $4 (
31... hxg6 32. Qd7 Qe7 33. Qg4 {White keeps a large advantage but the win
needs to be proved.}) 32. gxf7+ Kh8 33. Rg8#) 31. Qxe5 Re7 ({Perhaps Wojtaszek
missed the mate in the line:} 31... Bd6 32. hxg6 $1 Bxe5 33. gxf7+ Kf8 34. Rg8+
Ke7 35. f8=Q+ Kd7 36. Qd8#) 32. Qf4 a4 ({The pawn cannot be regained} 32...
Qxe4 33. Bxf7+) 33. Bd5 Qc7 {Basically, resignation. However, Black should not
survive after} (33... Qxc2 34. Rf3 Qc7 {Neither. For example} 35. Qd2 Bg7 36.
Rc1 Qb8 37. Rc4 {[%csl Rc7,Rc8,Rf7][%cal Gd2c2,Gc4c8,Rd5f7,Rc8g8,Rh5g6] with
the idea Qd2-c2.}) 34. Qd2 Qb6 35. Ra2 Rc7 36. Rf3 Qb4 37. Qe2 Rb6 38. hxg6
hxg6 39. g3 {In case of need, White can also attack on the "h" file.} Kg7 40.
Kg2 Rd7 41. Qd1 Rf6 {Allows the final small combination.} 42. Rxf6 $1 Kxf6 {
[%csl Rf6]} 43. c3 $1 dxc3 44. Rxa4 {Black resigned due to:} (44. Rxa4 Qxb2 45.
Qd4+ {[%csl Rf6]} Ke7 ({Or} 45... Kg5 46. Qh8 {and mate in seven.} (46. Qe5+ {
should also do.})) 46. Qe5+ Kd8 47. Ra8+) 1-0

