{[%evp 0,144,38,17,48,38,67,56,56,28,30,42,69,49,35,37,58,40,60,45,40,22,32,22,
23,24,24,18,18,3,14,-1,-1,-1,4,-3,0,0,9,5,15,-4,2,-16,-7,-7,2,-14,-15,-17,-12,
-98,-135,-126,-136,-130,0,1,0,0,0,0,63,-158,57,55,55,30,35,0,-22,-53,-57,-91,
-80,-68,-30,-43,-43,-39,-47,-92,-91,-127,-127,-134,-125,-124,-124,-124,-119,
-132,-122,-112,-119,-113,-117,-121,-147,-142,-172,-172,-172,-172,-172,-188,
-172,-172,-172,-172,-172,-172,-125,-143,-143,-172,-143,-143,-143,-162,-213,
-212,-135,-124,-132,-172,-180,-268,-293,-584,-682,-742,-912,-972,-982,-992,
-1011,-1012,-1022,-1022,-1022,-1032,-1032,-1032,-1242,-28192,-27688]} 1. e4 c5
2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3 a6 8. Qd2 h5 ({
Nakamura also plays this version of the Dragon, except that he goes directly
for queenside expansion with:} 8... b5 9. a4 b4 10. Nd5 Nxd5 11. exd5 Bb7 12.
Bc4 Nd7 13. a5 Nf6 14. Ne2 O-O 15. Ra4 Rc8 16. b3 Rc5 17. Rxb4 Rxd5 18. Bxd5
Bxd5 19. Rb6 {Kramnik,V (2808)-Nakamura,H (2785) Stavanger 2017}) 9. Bc4 Nbd7 {
Whereas Carlsen prefers to first develop before pushing the b-pawn.} 10. O-O-O
b5 11. Bb3 Nc5 $5 {[%mdl 4] An interesting side line, which the world champion
used last year too.} 12. Kb1 Bb7 13. Rhe1 {Dominguez does not want to follow
Grischuk's footprints.} ({In Saint Louis Carlsen faced:} 13. a3 {Which was a
novelty at the time. Grischuk later won, but it was not due to his superior
opening:} Nxb3 14. cxb3 Rc8 ({Another idea is to regroup with:} 14... Nd7 $5)
15. Nc2 ({A solid and good move was:} 15. Rhe1) 15... Qc7 16. Bd4 O-O ({
Here Carlsen could have equalized at once with:} 16... e5 $1 {[%cal Gd6d5]} 17.
Bf2 (17. Be3 d5 {would be similar.}) 17... d5 $1 {Then the forcing line:} 18.
Nxd5 Nxd5 19. exd5 Bxd5 20. Qxd5 Qxc2+ 21. Ka2 O-O {leads to equality.} ({
But not:} 21... Qxf2 $4 22. Qd7+ {[%csl Rc8,Re8][%cal Rd7c8,Rd7e8]})) 17. Qf2 (
{Although White already had a choice of interesting moves:} 17. Rc1 $5 {
was another one, overprotecting the knight on c2 and eyeballing the enemy
queen.}) 17... e5 ({Objectively, Carlsen should have defended patiently with:} 
17... e6 18. Rhe1 Qe7 19. Rd3 Rfd8 20. Red1 {but White is definitely enjoying
himself here.}) 18. Bb6 Qd7 ({Even worse is:} 18... Qc6 19. Nb4) 19. Nb4 Rxc3 (
{If:} 19... Qe6 20. Rd3 {then the rooks are doubled and Nd5 will be installed.}
) 20. bxc3 Qe6 21. Kb2 Rc8 ({Once more from objective point of view:} 21... d5
$1 {Was the best chance, although there too:} 22. exd5 Nxd5 23. Nxd5 Bxd5 {
White has the cold shower:} 24. Qc5 $1 Bxb3 25. Rd6 Qc4 26. Qxc4 Bxc4 27. Rhd1
{when the endgame is clearly better for White.}) 22. Ba5 {and eventually White
won in Grischuk,A (2777)-Carlsen,M (2863) St. Louis Rapid & Blitz 2020 [Bojkov,
Dejan]}) ({The predecessor (in this particular set-up) saw:} 13. Nd5 Rc8 14.
Bg5 e6 15. Nxf6+ Bxf6 16. h4 Qe7 17. Rhe1 Rd8 18. Bd5 $1 {[%csl Re7,Re8][%cal
Re1e8] The black king remained in the center after:} Bxg5 19. hxg5 e5 20. Nc6 (
20. Ne2 $1 {might have been better to occupy the central outpost later.}) 20...
Bxc6 21. Bxc6+ Kf8 {But after:} 22. f4 (22. Bd5 $1) 22... exf4 23. Qc3 $6 Kg8
24. e5 Kh7 25. Bd5 Rhe8 {Black managed to co-ordinate his pieces, Kulkarni,C 
(2355)-Nihal,S (2556) Abu Dhabi 2018}) ({It is curious to know the opinion of
the players regarding the computer shot:} 13. Nf5 $1 {[%cal Ge3c5] With the
idea:} gxf5 14. Bxc5 dxc5 15. Qg5 {[%csl Rd8,Rg7][%cal Rg5g7,Rd1d8] and White
wins. It seems as this line might be the acid test of Black's idea.}) 13... Rc8
14. Bg5 {[#]} O-O $146 {From transposition, players achieved an interesting
Dragon and Black simply castles which turn out to be a novelty. Carlsen was
probably happy that the opponent's rook has left the h-file and somewhat slows
his kingside attack.} ({The predecessor was:} 14... Nxb3 15. axb3 (15. cxb3 $1
{would have been more to the point.}) 15... Qc7 16. Re2 Qc5 17. f4 Nd7 $2 (
17... Nh7 $1 {[%csl Rg5][%cal Rh7g5]}) 18. e5 $1 {[%csl Rd7][%cal Gd4e6]} e6
19. exd6 O-O 20. Be7 {with an edge for White in Gao,H (1859)-Steadman,M (2242)
Auckland 2011}) 15. Nd5 {Dominguez provokes the e7-e6 move in order to create
a target on d6.} (15. h3 $5 {deserved attention anyway.}) 15... e6 16. Nxf6+
Bxf6 17. h4 {[%cal Ge1h1,Gh1h8] Opening the h-file at the end for his rook.} (
17. Bxf6 Qxf6 {is comfortable for Black.}) 17... Bxg5 18. hxg5 Kg7 19. Qe3 Qc7
({Aparently, the world champion did not want to see any white pieces occupying
the d5 spot in case of:} 19... e5 20. Ne2 a5 21. Bd5) 20. Rd2 ({Here:} 20. g4 {
is met with:} Rh8) 20... b4 21. Red1 Rfd8 ({Still:} 21... e5 $1 {deserved
serious attention, with good play for Black after:} 22. Ne2 a5 23. Bd5 Bxd5 24.
Rxd5 Rfd8 {[%cal Gc5e6]}) 22. Qf4 {Missing a perfect chance.} ({Once that the
black kingside rook moved, it was a good time for:} 22. g4 $1 {as} Rh8 ({
Also great for the first player is:} 22... hxg4 $6 23. Qf4) ({Perhaps
Dominguez did not like:} 22... h4 23. Qf4 Qe7 {But this is spectacularly
refuted with:} 24. Nf5+ $1 exf5 25. gxf5 gxf5 26. exf5 {[%csl Re7,Rg7][%cal
Gf5f6,Gf4h4,Gd2h2,Gd1h1,Gh1h8] with huge attack for the sacrificed piece.}) 23.
Qf4 Qe7 24. e5 $1 {[%csl Rg7] is very nice for White.}) 22... Qe7 23. Ne2 ({
No time now for:} 23. g4 $2 e5) 23... a5 ({Correct was the preliminary:} 23...
e5 $1 24. Qh4 a5) {Now Dominguez goes for the strong:} 24. e5 $1 d5 25. g4 {
But misses a nice detail. This move is natural and not best...} ({Both players
missed that White could have brought his bishop back into the game with:} 25.
Bc4 $1 {[%cal Gc4b5,Gc4d3,Gd3g6] When:} dxc4 $2 {loses to:} 26. Qf6+ {[%csl
Rd8,Re7][%cal Rd2d8] That means that the bishop would be brought back into the
scene and it would have gone either to d3 or sometimes even on b5, causing
havoc in Black's camp. Dominguez would have had the advantage then.}) 25...
hxg4 26. Qf6+ Qxf6 27. gxf6+ ({After:} 27. exf6+ Kf8 {the king escapes and
Black's central pawn would become a significant factor.}) 27... Kh6 {Played
without much thought. Carlsen trusts his position.} ({It would have been equal
after the safer:} 27... Kf8 28. fxg4 Ne4 29. Rd4 Ke8 30. a3 bxa3 31. Ra4 axb2
32. Rxa5 Ra8 (32... Kd7) 33. Rxa8 Rxa8 34. Kxb2) 28. Rh1+ {Alas! After
spending his last minute on the clock Dominguez could not find the study-like
with!} ({He could have checkmated the champion instead with:} 28. Rd4 $3 gxf3 {
With the brilliant point:} 29. Rg4 $3 {Setting a cage for the king. It is not
yet over:} Kh5 30. Rg3 g5 {Seems as the king escapes but there comes one last
super-move:} 31. Nf4+ $3 {[%csl Rg6][%cal Rh5g6,Rf4g6] Not letting the king
back.} ({Otherwise Black wins after:} 31. Rh1+ Kg6 $1) 31... Kh4 (31... gxf4
32. Rh1#) 32. Rdg1 gxf4 33. Rg7 {[%csl Rh4][%cal Rg7h7,Rg1h1] with inevitable
mate.}) 28... Kg5 29. f4+ {It is still very dangerous for the king but Carlsen
navigates with amazing precision.} Kf5 30. Rf1 g5 $1 {[%csl Re5,Rf4,Gf5][%cal
Gf5e5] The only move which saves the king and destroys the opponent's pawn
chain.} 31. Nd4+ Kg6 (31... Ke4 $1 32. fxg5 Kxe5) 32. f5+ exf5 33. Nxf5 g3 $1 {
Again, an only move.} ({It is not too late to be mated:} 33... Ne4 34. Ne7+ Kh5
35. Rh2#) 34. Rg2 ({After:} 34. Nxg3 Ne4 {[%csl Re5,Rf6,Gg6] Black finally
stops the attack and can start picking up the pawns.}) ({And the pawn on g5
that Carlsen hugely risked keeping :} 34. Ne7+ Kh5 35. Rh1+ Kg4 36. Rd4+ Ne4
37. Nxc8 Rxc8 38. Bxd5 Bxd5 39. Rxd5 Rc5 $1 {[%cal Gg3g2,Gg4g3] would win for
Black.}) 34... Ne4 35. Nxg3 Re8 {Carlsen survived the attack and now has a
brilliant king into the endgame. He is ready to pick up all the white pawns.}
36. Nxe4 dxe4 37. e6 $1 {Excellent defense by Dominguez.} fxe6 38. f7 Rf8 39.
Bxe6 Rc5 40. Rg3 {Playing with a few seconds on the clock is not easy for
anyone, and Dominguez commits a fatal inaccuracy. He needed to get his king
out of the back-rank problems asap instead.} ({White came close to the draw
and he might have achieved it with:} 40. Kc1 $1 e3 41. Rg3 Re5 42. Bc4) 40...
Re5 41. Bg4 e3 42. Kc1 ({Alas, no time for:} 42. Re1 Rxf7 43. Rgxe3 Rxe3 44.
Rxe3 Rf1+) 42... Rxf7 43. Rxf7 Kxf7 {The converting phase starts. Until a
moment, Carlsen had everything under control.} 44. Kd1 Kf6 45. Ke1 Bd5 46. a3
bxa3 47. bxa3 Be4 {The world champion knows that he would be winning the
bishop endgame, even though one of his remaining pawns is promoted in the
wrong corner.} 48. Rxe3 Bxc2 49. Kd2 Rxe3 50. Kxe3 Ke5 51. Bf3 Bf5 {If White
can only trade his bishop for the g-pawn and sneak into the a1 corner, that
would be a draw, but there is no way Carlsen would allow that.} 52. Bc6 Kd6 53.
Bf3 Kc5 54. Be2 Bg6 55. Bf1 Bh5 56. Ke4 Bd1 57. Ke3 ({Or:} 57. Kf5 g4 58. Kf4
Kd4 {making it to the a3 pawn.}) 57... g4 58. Ba6 Bf3 59. Bf1 Bc6 60. Kf4 Kd4 {
Misses the win! What was the rush for?} ({A neat finish would have been:} 60...
Bb5 $1 61. Bg2 Bd7 {as White cannot prevent the enemy king from breaking
through:} 62. Ke3 Kc4 {[%csl Ra3][%cal Gc4b3,Gb3a3]}) 61. Kxg4 Kc3 62. Kf5 {
A step in the wrong direction.} ({The king needed to get into the corner,
therefore:} 62. Be2 $1 {[%cal Re2d1] In order to have Be2-d1 maneuver any time
the opponent pushed his a-pawn would have been one way to draw. A typical line
runs:} Kb3 63. Kf4 Kxa3 64. Ke3 Kb4 65. Bd1 Ba4 66. Bxa4 Kxa4 67. Kd2 Kb3 68.
Kc1) (62. Kf4 $1 {would also do.}) 62... Kb2 63. Ke5 Kxa3 64. Kd6 ({It was not
too late for:} 64. Kf4 $1 {with a textbook draw.}) 64... Be8 65. Kc5 a4 {
Now the white king is left behind the pawn and cannot help it. The three black
units quickly outnumber the bishop. Notice that the a-pawn is far more
dangerous than the more central pawns as the white bishop can only stop it
from one diagonal.} 66. Bc4 Kb2 67. Kb4 a3 68. Bd5 Bg6 69. Be6 Bb1 70. Bd5 Ba2
71. Be4 Bf7 72. Bb1 Bb3 0-1

