{[%evp 0,75,21,41,41,59,75,63,63,41,41,26,62,40,92,74,58,52,52,61,39,-5,8,22,
30,-8,63,63,41,59,41,33,20,7,69,98,98,70,81,81,72,84,156,139,147,147,144,110,
111,111,97,100,110,96,115,132,117,109,133,128,136,142,142,108,220,260,252,226,
530,226,418,475,497,734,1237,1303,1322,1322]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4.
Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be2 e6 7. Be3 Be7 {Black often delays this move in these
Siccilians, trying to get some space and play on the opposite wing first (or
in the center.)} 8. g4 {[%csl Rd7][%cal Gg4g5,Rb8d7,Rf6d7] A sharp attacking
continuation against the Scheweningen in the spirit of the Keres Atatck..} b5 {
A very risky move which the world champion executed after more than twelve
minutes spent on his clock. The last time this was tried was back in 2016.} ({
A recent grandmaster game saw an even sharper development after:} 8... Nfd7 9.
Qd2 b5 10. a3 Bb7 11. O-O-O Nc6 12. g5 $5 {[%csl Rg5][%cal Gg1g7]} Nxd4 13.
Qxd4 Bxg5 14. Rhg1 Bxe3+ 15. Qxe3 Qb6 16. Qg3 Ne5 17. f4 Ng6 18. f5 Ne5 19.
fxe6 fxe6 20. Qxg7 O-O-O {[%csl Gc8,Ge5] Tarlev,K (2564)-Saric,I (2650)
Germany 2019}) ({Eight years back in Norway, V. Topalov played in accordance
with the classical principles and striked in the center:} 8... d5 9. exd5 Nxd5
10. Nxd5 Qxd5 11. Bf3 Qa5+ 12. Qd2 Qxd2+ 13. Bxd2 Nd7 {[%csl Gf3] comfortably
holding the endgame in Nakamura,H (2775)-Topalov,V (2793) Stavanger 2013}) 9.
g5 {Esipenko in returns plays quickly and confidently.} Nfd7 10. a3 $1 {
[%csl Rg5][%cal Re7g5] Played without any hesitation. It is far more important
to stabilize the center than to care for the g5 pawn. White is often
sacrificing it anyway whenever the opponent castles short for instanse.} ({
After:} 10. Qd2 Bb7 (10... b4 11. Nd1 Nc5 {might be even more interesting.})
11. a3 Nb6 12. b3 N8d7 13. f4 Rc8 14. Bf3 Qc7 15. Nce2 g6 16. c3 Nc5 {[%csl
Gb6,Gb7,Gc5,Gc7,Gc8,Ge4][%cal Gc5e4,Gb7e4] Black achieved harmonious position
in Ashiku,F (2139)-Ten Hertog,H (2318) Albena 2011}) 10... Bxg5 {Again
hesitation. But what else?} ({After:} 10... Bb7 11. Rg1 Qc7 12. f4 {[%csl Ge4,
Gf4,Gg5] White has an excellent attacking position for free.}) 11. Qd2 Bxe3 ({
Esipenko, no doubt knew the following masterpiece:} 11... Bf6 12. O-O-O Bb7 13.
Rhg1 Nc5 14. e5 $3 {[%csl Re5] In the best-defended spot!} Bxe5 (14... dxe5 15.
Ndxb5 $1 {would not have changed anything.}) 15. Ndxb5 $1 {[%csl Rc5][%cal
Re3c5]} Nb3+ (15... axb5 16. Bxc5) 16. cxb3 axb5 17. Bxb5+ Bc6 18. Bd4 Qc8 19.
Bxe5 dxe5 20. Kb1 Rg8 21. Ne4 {1-0 (21) Ivanchuk,V (2739)-Negi,P (2634)
Peristeri 2010}) 12. Qxe3 {[%csl Ra8,Rb8,Gc3,Rc8,Gd4,Rd6,Rd7,Ge2,Ge3,Rg7][%cal
Gh1g1,Gg1g7,Gd1d6] For the pawn, the young Russian GM has a significant lead
in the development and a lot of open files to work on. The pawns on d6 and g7
are particularly interesting for White. [#]} Qh4 $146 {This is also hard to
explain. Carlsen is lagging in development. Why does he not develop pieces?
And who is going to defend now the d6 pawn?} ({The predecessor was en email
game which saw the more reasonable:} 12... Bb7 13. O-O-O Qe7 14. Nb3 Nc6 15.
Qg3 Nc5 16. Nxc5 dxc5 17. Qxg7 Rf8 18. Bg4 Nd4 19. Ne2 O-O-O {[%csl Gc8]
Frotscher,T (2363)-Gomila Marti,S (2375) ICCF email 2019}) 13. Rg1 {Of course!
White is not afraid of losing the h2 pawn.} g6 ({In fact in the line:} 13...
Qxh2 14. Rxg7 Qh1+ {He has a spectacular win:} 15. Kd2 $3 {[%csl Rh1][%cal
Ra1h1]} Qxa1 16. Nxe6 $1 {[%csl Re8][%cal Gc3d5]} fxe6 17. Qg5 {[%cal Rg5e7]
with mate.}) ({Understandably Black does not want to castle under an attack:} 
13... O-O 14. O-O-O) 14. O-O-O Qe7 15. f4 {The central breaks are in the air.}
Bb7 16. Kb1 {A cunning move. White often does this prophylaxis in the Sicilian,
but here it is more venomous than it seems and it sets a nasty trap.} ({
Other logical and strong continuations were:} 16. h4) ({Or:} 16. e5 {with the
idea:} d5 17. f5 $1 {[%csl Gf5] to reach the black king as quick as possible.})
16... Nc6 {Carlsen falls for it!} ({We know why he does not want to castle:} 
16... O-O 17. h4 {Many files will be opened against his king in a flash.}) ({
However, the preliminary:} 16... Nc5 {was a must and only after:} 17. Bf3 Nc6 {
True, even here Black's position remains suspicious, to say at least after:}
18. e5 d5 19. Bxd5 $1 {[%cal Rc3d5,Rd5f6] A sacrifice which Black cannot
accept:} exd5 20. Nxd5 {as the queen does not have a reasonable square.}) 17.
Ncxb5 $1 {That's it! After the forcing:} axb5 18. Nxc6 Bxc6 19. Qc3 $1 {
[%csl Rc6,Rh8][%cal Rc3c6,Rc3h8] Which Black missed the world champion can
already resign, on move nineteen. An exceptional case in his practice.} O-O 20.
Qxc6 d5 {Trying to complicate as much as possible.} ({Nothing changes:} 20...
Nc5 21. Qxd6 Qa7 22. Qd4) 21. exd5 Rfc8 22. d6 $1 {But Esipenko is very
accurate.} Qd8 (22... Rxc6 23. dxe7 {promotes.}) 23. Qxb5 {Looks risky but it
was very carefully calculated.} ({More careful player would have chosen:} 23.
Qe4 {but the young Rusian has it all covered.}) 23... Rcb8 24. Qc4 Rxa3 {
For a moment, it seems as the world champion might muddy the waters, however...
} 25. Qc7 Qe8 26. Rg5 $1 {[%cal Gg5b5,Gb5a5] Is a nice, decisive maneuver that
aims to trade one of the enemy rooks, thus killing all the attacks.} Ra4 ({
Since:} 26... Rc8 {is refuted by:} 27. bxa3 $1) 27. Ra5 Rab4 28. b3 R4b7 ({
After:} 28... Rc8 {The neatest win is:} 29. Bb5 $1 {[%csl Rd6,Rd7][%cal Rc7d7]}
Rxc7 30. dxc7 {[%cal Gc7c8] when the pawn cannot be stopped.}) 29. Qc3 {
The attack is over before it even began. Esipenko comfortably finishes the
battle.} Qd8 30. Bf3 Rb4 31. Qc7 Qf6 32. Ra8 {Finally achieving his goal.} Rxa8
33. Bxa8 Qf5 34. Kb2 Rb5 35. Qxd7 Rc5 36. Rc1 Qxf4 37. Qe8+ Kg7 38. d7 1-0

