{[%evp 0,42,20,24,52,60,80,75,75,42,43,28,56,3,58,49,34,-43,-30,-58,-32,-67,
-78,-139,15,-10,-3,11,25,24,21,21,30,3,2,-44,-43,-77,-34,-172,-92,8,37,283,
1213]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Rg1 {[%cal Gg2g4,
Gg4g5] Long time no see of this line. Actually, the last time I remember a top
player used it, it was Magnus Carlsen who tried it as White!} b5 7. g4 {
The point behind White's idea. The sooner the pawn runs, the earlier the
knight will have to leave the active f6 square. The question is who is faster?}
Bb7 8. g5 {Or who is braver?} ({The game mentioned above saw:} 8. f3 g6 9. a3
Bg7 10. Be3 Nbd7 11. Qd2 Rc8 12. O-O-O Ne5 13. Be2 Nc4 14. Bxc4 Rxc4 15. Kb1
O-O 16. h4 Nd7 17. h5 {[%cal Gh1g1] Carlsen,M (2876)-Sjugirov,S (2662) chess24.
com INT 2020}) 8... Nxe4 9. Nxe4 Bxe4 {[#]} 10. a4 $146 {Nepomniachcthi is
blitzing his move, including this novelty!} ({The predecessor was:} 10. Qg4 Bb7
11. Bg2 Qc7 12. Be3 g6 13. O-O-O Bg7 14. f4 O-O 15. h4 Nd7 16. Bxb7 Qxb7 17. f5
Ne5 18. Qh3 Qe4 {with a mess, Petrosian,T (2568)-Smirnov,P (2645) Moscow 2005})
10... e5 ({After the natural:} 10... bxa4 {White can activate his rooks a'la
Tal:} 11. Rxa4 {[%cal Ga4e4]} Bb7 ({Cutting the bishop away from the queenside
with:} 11... d5 12. Bb5+ Nd7 13. Bc6 Rc8 14. Rxa6 {[%csl Re8] is quite risky
for Black as well.}) 12. Rb4 Qc7 13. Rg3 {[%csl Rb7][%cal Gg3c3,Gb4b7,Rc3c7]
intending Rg3-c3. This looks so much like the first game of the first WW match
between Tal and Botvinnik.}) 11. axb5 $1 {Again blitzed out. And after long (a
bit more than five minutes for rapid a lot!) thought the world champion
decided not to accept the "gift".} Be7 $1 ({Even with proper preparation Black
can hardly enter:} 11... exd4 12. Qxd4 d5 13. Rg3 $5 {[%csl Re8][%cal Gg3e3,
Re3e8]} ({Also good seems the simple capture:} 13. bxa6) 13... Nd7 14. Re3 {
The black king is exposed and while Black defends it:} Be7 15. Qxg7 Rf8 {
He gets under attack practically for free after:} 16. f3 ({Or:} 16. bxa6)) 12.
Rg4 $1 {[%csl Gg4][%cal Gg4h4,Gg4e4,Ge4a4] This strong maneuver again! The
rook is eyeing both the flanks.} axb5 ({The kingside retreat:} 12... Bg6 13.
Qf3 d5 14. Nf5 Bxf5 15. Qxf5 O-O {abandons the queenside and White wins the
battle there with:} 16. Rga4 {[%csl Ra6][%cal Gb5a6]}) 13. Bxb5+ Nd7 ({Maybe
objectively better was the awkward looking:} 13... Kf8 $5 14. Rxa8 Bxa8 15. Nb3
Nd7 16. Be3 {although White is calling the shots here as well. Above all,
Black misses his kingside rook.}) 14. Bd2 {[%cal Gd1a1] The best reply again
by Nepomniachtchi. The Russian player keeps the pressure on and passes the
ball back into Carlsen's court.} ({Black does not fear:} 14. Rxa8 Qxa8 15. Qe2
Bb7 16. Bxd7+ Kxd7 17. Qb5+ Bc6) 14... Bb7 {After another heavy thought, the
bishop goes back home} ({Of course not:} 14... exd4 15. Rxe4) ({Neither:} 14...
Rxa1 15. Qxa1 Bd5 16. Nc6 {with a clear edge for White in both cases.}) 15. Nf5
{Closer, and closer...} O-O {Finally Carlsen castles, but that is not the end
of his problems.} ({Computer recommends:} 15... g6 16. Rxa8 Bxa8 17. Nxe7 Kxe7
18. Ra4 {But this can hardly be recommended... Black's king is permanently
weak.}) 16. Rxa8 {The first moment in which Nepomniachtchi did not find the
best continuation.} ({The amazing resource:} 16. Rga4 $3 Rxa4 17. Rxa4 {
[%csl Rb7,Rd7][%cal Ga4a7,Ra7b7,Rb7d7] Practically led to Black's zugzwang.
The simple threat Ra4-a7 cannot be stopped. For instance:} Nc5 ({If:} 17... Re8
18. Ra7 Qc7 {is best refuted with the nice:} 19. Qf3 $1 {[%csl Rb7,Rc7,Rd7,Re7]
[%cal Rf3b7,Ra7b7]}) 18. Ba5 $1 {and Black drops material.}) 16... Bxa8 17. Rh4
$1 {This is why the problems are not over. The king is in danger on the
kingside as well. What an amazing rook this one is!} g6 $1 {The only move.} ({
Everything else loses. Like:} 17... Bxg5 18. Bxg5 Qxg5 19. Bxd7) ({Or:} 17...
h6 18. Qh5 {with decisive threats.}) 18. Qg4 $1 {[%csl Rh7][%cal Rg4h3,Rh3h7]
Almost all the white pieces join forces.} Nc5 {One more only move.} ({Mate is
unstoppable after:} 18... gxf5 19. Qxf5 {[%csl Rh7][%cal Rf5h7]}) ({And Black
loses on the spot too after:} 18... Re8 19. Nh6+ {[%csl Rf7]}) 19. Qh3 {
The culmination of the game. Lacking time, Carlsen blunders:} h5 ({As
desperate as Black's position seemed, there was a way out:} 19... Bxg5 $1 20.
Rxh7 Bxd2+ 21. Kxd2 Qg5+ {Suddenly reveals that the white king is not
perfectly safe neither: Now:} 22. Kc3 {is best.} ({As the other retreats even
lose for the first player:} 22. Ke2 $2 Qxf5 23. Rh8+ Kg7 24. Qh7+ Kf6 25. Rxf8
Qxc2+ {[%csl Re2] and Black gets his hands on the white king first.}) ({
Similar to that:} 22. Kd1 $2 {is insufficient and it is the white king that is
suffering first after:} gxf5 23. Rh8+ Kg7 24. Qh7+ Kf6 25. Rxf8 Bf3+ 26. Be2
Qg1+ {[%cal Rc5e4] and mate.}) 22... Ne4+ ({It is too early for:} 22... gxf5 $2
23. Rh8+ Kg7 24. Qh7+ Kf6 25. Rxf8) 23. Kb4 {Now both:} Qd2+ ({And:} 23... gxf5
24. Rh8+ Kg7 25. Qh7+ Kf6 26. Rxf8 Qd2+ {is perpetual check too.}) 24. Ka3 Qa5+
25. Ba4 Qc5+ 26. Ka2 Qc4+ 27. Ka3 Qc5+ {lead to a draw by force.}) 20. Rxh5 $3
{[%csl Rg8][%cal Rh5h8] This is it! Black is getting checkmated.} gxh5 21. Qxh5
Ne6 ({Perhaps the world champion missed:} 21... Bf6 22. Qh6 $1 {[%cal Rg5f6,
Rh6g7]} Bh8 23. g6 {[%cal Rh6h7]} fxg6 24. Qxg6+ Bg7 25. Qxg7#) ({Carlsen
resigned before his kingside got decimated:} 21... Ne6 22. g6 fxg6 23. Qxg6+
Kh8 24. Qh6+ Kg8 25. Qxe6+) 1-0

