{[%evp 0,91,28,43,44,44,79,41,55,26,35,35,49,40,43,32,43,29,51,44,40,27,27,22,
22,25,25,17,10,12,12,2,10,13,9,-7,27,29,26,31,76,76,76,76,159,153,213,213,213,
213,213,231,255,260,371,371,324,207,225,225,224,215,221,221,221,221,221,221,
229,215,226,226,226,226,220,220,229,214,205,203,259,192,231,211,252,248,248,
191,248,274,274,255,450,478]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3
g6 {An interesting choice for the decisive game. Carlsen does not stick to any
solid opening, but chooses instead one of the sharpest Sicilian lines- the
Dragon.} 6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3 a6 {A rare move.} 8. Qd2 h5 ({Nakamura could not
solve his opening problems completely in the following game:} 8... b5 9. a4 b4
10. Nd5 Nxd5 11. exd5 Bb7 12. Bc4 Nd7 13. a5 Nf6 14. Ne2 O-O 15. Ra4 Rc8 16. b3
Rc5 17. Rxb4 Rxd5 18. Bxd5 Bxd5 19. Rb6 {Kramnik,V (2808)-Nakamura,H (2785)
Stavanger 2017}) 9. Bc4 Nbd7 10. Bb3 Nc5 11. O-O-O {[%csl Rc5][%cal Re3c5]
Grischuk follows the classical traditions and develops a piece with every move
that he makes.} b5 12. Kb1 (12. Nf5 $2 Nxb3+) 12... Bb7 {[#]} 13. a3 $146 ({
The predecessor saw:} 13. Nd5 Rc8 14. Bg5 e6 15. Nxf6+ Bxf6 16. h4 Qe7 17. Rhe1
Rd8 18. Bd5 $1 {The black king remained in the center after:} Bxg5 19. hxg5 e5
20. Nc6 (20. Ne2 $1 {might have been better to occupy the central outpost
later.}) 20... Bxc6 21. Bxc6+ Kf8 {But after:} 22. f4 (22. Bd5 $1) 22... exf4
23. Qc3 $6 Kg8 24. e5 Kh7 25. Bd5 Rhe8 {Black managed to co-ordinate his
pieces, Kulkarni,C (2355)-Nihal,S (2556) Abu Dhabi 2018}) ({It is curious to
know the opinion of the players regarding the computer shot:} 13. Nf5 $1 {
With the idea:} gxf5 14. Bxc5 dxc5 15. Qg5 {and White wins. It seems as this
line might be the acid test of Black's idea.}) 13... Nxb3 14. cxb3 Rc8 {
Natural and strong.} ({Another idea is to regroup with:} 14... Nd7 $5) 15. Nc2
{[%cal Gc3d5,Ge4d5,Gc2b4,Gb4d5] Grischuk tries to block the central pawns and
deprive his opponent of any counterplay.} ({A solid and good move was:} 15.
Rhe1) 15... Qc7 16. Bd4 {This regrouping is what the Russian GM had in mind.
d6-d5 is no longer possible. Or at least it seems so.} O-O {Missing the moment.
} ({Carlsen could have equalized at once with:} 16... e5 $1 17. Bf2 (17. Be3 d5
{would be similar.}) 17... d5 $1 {[%csl Gd5] Then the forcing line:} 18. Nxd5
Nxd5 19. exd5 Bxd5 20. Qxd5 Qxc2+ 21. Ka2 O-O {leads to equality.} ({But not:} 
21... Qxf2 $4 22. Qd7+)) 17. Qf2 {Another excellent prophylaxis.} ({Although
White already had a choice of interesting moves:} 17. Rc1 $5 {was another one,
overprotecting the knight on c2 and eyeballing the enemy queen.}) 17... e5 {
A move too late, and it already does not work. The Sicilian Defense, ladies
and gentlemen!} ({Objectively, Carlsen should have defended patiently with:} 
17... e6 18. Rhe1 Qe7 19. Rd3 Rfd8 20. Red1 {[%csl Rd6] but White is
definitely enjoying himself here.}) 18. Bb6 {With a tempo.} Qd7 ({Even worse
is:} 18... Qc6 19. Nb4) 19. Nb4 $1 {If White manages to install a knight on d5
Black's position will become strategically lost; therefore :} Rxc3 {Was played
without hesitation.} ({If:} 19... Qe6 20. Rd3 {[%csl Rg7][%cal Gh1d1,Gb4d5]
then the rooks are doubled and Nd5 will be installed.}) 20. bxc3 Qe6 21. Kb2
Rc8 {Still hoping for a much-needed tempo to build enough initiative, but
Grischuk will never give it.} ({Once more from an objective point of view:} 
21... d5 $1 {Was the best chance, although there too:} 22. exd5 Nxd5 23. Nxd5
Bxd5 {White has the cold shower:} 24. Qc5 $1 Bxb3 25. Rd6 Qc4 26. Qxc4 Bxc4 27.
Rhd1 {when the endgame is clearly better for White.}) 22. Ba5 d5 ({An
interesting sacrifice would have been:} 22... Bxe4 {With the idea:} 23. fxe4 ({
However, both:} 23. Qb6 $1) ({And:} 23. Qd2 $1 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Rd2d6] calm
moves would have refuted Black's idea.}) 23... Nxe4 24. Qb6 Nxc3 25. Rxd6 Na4+
26. bxa4 e4+ {[%csl Rb3][%cal Ge6b3] and Black is crushing.}) 23. Qa7 $1 Ba8
24. Nxa6 {Again the strongest move. Grischuk plugs in the half-open c-file and
stops any attacking options.} ({The endgame after:} 24. Qxa6 Qxa6 25. Nxa6 dxe4
{is better for White, but not as clear.}) 24... Bf8 ({A neat tactical point
behind Grischuk's play was:} 24... dxe4 25. Nc7 Qc6 26. Nxa8 Rxa8 27. Qxa8+ $1
{[%csl Ra8,Rc6]} Qxa8 28. Rd8+) ({Whereas:} 24... d4 {can be met with the
cementing:} 25. Rc1) 25. Nc7 Qe7 26. Nxb5 Qe8 27. Nc7 Qe7 28. Bb6 $1 {[%csl
Ra8][%cal Gc7a8] That is it! Everything is defended, and White is trading the
key attackers.} dxe4 29. Nxa8 Qxa7 30. Bxa7 Rxa8 31. Bf2 Bxa3+ 32. Kc2 Be7 33.
Ra1 {The endgame is lost for Carlsen.} Rc8 34. Rhd1 exf3 35. gxf3 e4 36. fxe4
Nxe4 37. Bd4 f5 38. Kb2 {Last preparation, after which the queenside passers
come into motion.} ({The pawns would have moved a bit faster with:} 38. Ra7 Kf7
39. b4) 38... Kf7 39. b4 g5 40. Kb3 g4 ({Nothing changes:} 40... h4 41. Ra7 Ke6
) 41. Ra7 Ke6 42. Ra6+ Kf7 43. c4 Bd6 44. Bg1 Ke7 45. c5 Be5 46. Rd5 1-0

