L (2408) Paris 2019}) 9... exf4 {Played a tempo. Vachier-Lagrave does not
intend to allow f4-f5.} 10. Bxf4 {Or else Le will have to part with his
dark-squared bishop.} ({As in the line:} 10. gxf4 h6 {It cannot retreat:} 11.
Bh4 {Due to the famous tactic:} Nxe4 $1 {[%csl Rc3,Rd1][%cal Re7h4,Re4c3,Rc3d1]
} 12. Bxe7 Nxc3 {With better endgame for Black after either:} 13. Qxd6 ({Or:} 
13. Bxd8 Nxd1 14. Rxd1 Kxd8) 13... Qxe7) 10... Nc6 11. Qd2 O-O 12. O-O-O Ne5 {
The most obvious reply. Both sides prepare for play on their flanks and Black
can be happy with the opening outcome.} ({Also attractive was:} 12... Rc8 $5 {
As Black, as a rule, is not afraid to sacrifice the d6 pawn as in line:} 13.
Bxd6 Bg4 14. Bxe7 Qxe7 15. Re1 Ne5) 13. Nd4 {An accurate move.} ({White could
have played this on the next move, after something useful like:} 13. Kb1 Rc8
14. Nd4 (14. Be2 $5) {However, then Black would have had additional choice:}
14... Bg4 15. Be2 Nc4 {[%cal Rg4d1]}) 13... Bd7 ({Here:} 13... Bg4 14. Be2 {
does not make sense for Black.}) 14. Kb1 Rc8 15. h3 {Too sluggish!} ({Instead:
} 15. Nf5 $5 {[%csl Rd6,Re7,Gf5][%cal Gf5d6,Gf5e7]} Bxf5 16. exf5 {seemed more
reasonable. The bishop on e6 is a very dangerous piece.}) 15... b5 {Now
Vachier-Lagrave would be the first one to push his knight pawn in the battle
for the vital central squares.} 16. a3 {Once again Le is not afraid to light a
match near the queenside petrol station.} ({Black is comfortable after:} 16. g4
b4 17. Nd5 Nxd5 18. exd5 a5 {though.}) 16... Qb6 17. g4 b4 {This is the reason
why h2-h3 migth be too slow. Vachier-Lagrave is the first one to open the
opponent's queenside. On the top of that the Frenchman had massive lead on the
clock.} 18. axb4 Qxb4 19. g5 Rxc3 $1 {The only move, but a good one.} ({
Any retreat loses:} 19... Nh5 $2 {For instance drops a piece after:} 20. Nd5
Qxd2 21. Nxe7+ Kh8 22. Bxd2) 20. gxf6 $1 {Best. But Vachier-Lagrave keeps
blitzing the strongest moves.} ({Black has more than enough for the exchange
in case of:} 20. Qxc3 Qxc3 21. bxc3 Nxe4 {[%csl Rc3,Rd1,Rh1][%cal Ge4c3,Ge4f2,
Gf2d1,Gf2h1]}) 20... Rb8 $1 21. Nb3 {Le spent his last remaining few minutes,
but could not find the amazing resource.} ({The stunning:} 21. Nb5 $3 {[%csl
Rb5] Would have kept White alive:} Bxb5 {[%cal Rb8b5,Rb5b1]} 22. Qxc3 ({
No time for:} 22. fxe7 Ba4 {[%csl Rb2][%cal Rb4b2]}) 22... Qxc3 23. bxc3 {
Leads to a position which is pleasant for Black after:} Bxf6 $1 ({Less good is:
} 23... Bxf1+ 24. Kc1 Bxf6 25. Rhxf1 {although here too Black should not
complain too much.})) 21... Rxb3 $1 {[%csl Rb1,Rh1][%cal Rb4e4,Re4b1,Re4h1]
Third strong blow in a row.} 22. cxb3 Qxe4+ 23. Ka1 {Now it all finishes in a
jiffy.} ({But perhaps Le did not even seriously consider:} 23. Bd3 $1 Nxd3 24.
Qxd3 {When Black is having large advantage after both:} Qxf4 ({Or:} 24... Qxd3+
25. Rxd3 Bf5 26. fxe7 Bxd3+ 27. Ka2 Re8 {[%csl Re7][%cal Gf7f6,Gg8f7,Rf7e7]
followed by f7-f6.}) 25. Rhf1 Qh4 26. fxe7 Qxe7 {but perhaps White could have
saved this?!}) 23... Bxf6 24. Bg2 Nf3 $1 25. Qe3 {Leads to mate.} ({But
nothing would have been changed after:} 25. Bxf3 Qxf3 26. Qxd6 Bxb2+) 25... Qc2
{[%csl Rb2][%cal Rc2b2,Rb8b3,Rb3a3]} 0-1

